There are 103 cases of irido-ciliary epithelial tumors in cats (Figs 9.54
, 9.55
) in the COPLOW collection. Together, these constitute 2% of the feline submissions and 3.7% of feline ocular neoplasms.•Irido-ciliary epithelial tumors are the fourth most common intraocular neoplasm in cats, following diffuse iris melanoma, lymphoma and post-traumatic sarcoma•The signalment of affected cats may be summarized as follows:▪The average age of affected cats is 9.1 years▪Affected cats by gender (where known)–Males: 6–Neutered males: 45–Females: 1–Spayed females: 39

•Feline irido-ciliary epithelial tumors generally fill the posterior chamber, cradle the lens equator, and infiltrate the iris, ciliary body, anterior chamber, and rarely the inner sclera•Morphologic features of feline irido-ciliary epithelial tumors: (Fig. 9.56
)▪These tumors are almost always composed of non-pigmented epithelial cells▪They seldom contain cords or ribbons of epithelial cells; rather, they are composed of solid sheets of polygonal cells which can be difficult to recognize as being epithelial▪There is a delicate but very regular vascular stroma which subtly subdivides the tumor mass into small subunits, and is made more apparent with the PAS stain▪About 30% of feline irido-ciliary adenomas have metaplastic bone within the mass▪The solid sheets of tumor tissue are often interrupted by cavitated cystic spaces. Occasionally, the tumors are predominantly cystic.
